data.content:
**Yes, C# fully supports `stackalloc`'d `Span<nint>` and `Span<nuint>`.** It works just like any other unmanaged type with `stackalloc`:

```csharp
Span<nint>  span  = stackalloc nint[5];
Span<nuint> uspan = stackalloc nuint[3];
```

On this 64-bit system each element is 8 bytes. The only caveat is that `sizeof(nint)` requires an `unsafe` context (since `nint`/`nuint` don't have a compile-time-known size), but the `stackalloc` itself works fine in safe code when assigned to a `Span<T>`.
